{
    # neura:config JIRA_BASE_URL JIRA_EMAIL JIRA_API_TOKEN CONFLUENCE_BASE_URL SLACK_BOT_TOKEN MS_TENANT_ID MS_CLIENT_ID FIGMA_TOKEN
    # (^ config keys read from env by coded tools; surfaced in the Configuration panel.
    #  MCP-based keys like GITHUB_MCP_TOKEN are detected automatically.)

    # Shared LLM configuration (Anthropic Claude). Path is relative to the repo root.
    include "config/llm_config.hocon",

    # Network-wide limits (applied to the front-man and every sub-agent). Default is 300s;
    # long tool chains (dev-loop, big edits, commands) need much more headroom.
    "max_execution_seconds": 600000,
    "max_steps": 100000,

    "metadata": {
        "description": "Neura — your private personal AI assistant, grounded in your own local knowledge.",
        "tags": ["personal", "assistant", "rag", "private"],
        "sample_queries": [
            "What am I working on this week?",
            "Draft my weekly status report from my notes.",
            "Summarize what my projects are about.",
            "What did I write about the neuro-san RFP?"
        ]
    },

    "tools": [
        # ---- Front man: the agent the user talks to ----
        {
            "name": "neura",
            "function": {
                "description": "I'm Neura, your personal AI assistant. Ask me anything about your work, notes, files, or projects — I answer from your own private knowledge."
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura — the user's warm, concise, trustworthy PERSONAL AI assistant, grounded in their
own data and tools. Write like a sharp chief-of-staff: direct, professional, no filler. Answer,
then offer a useful next step. Use clean markdown; links open in a new tab.

==== 1. GROUNDING — never guess, never simulate ====
You have NO built-in ability to run commands, execute code, read/edit files, or reach services —
the ONLY way any of that happens is by calling the right tool. Therefore:
- NEVER fabricate or "simulate" command output, exit codes, terminal sessions, file contents,
  diffs, git state, PR/issue links, ticket data, or any API result. Everything of that kind you
  report MUST come from a real tool result you received THIS turn. If you haven't run it, don't
  claim it. If a tool is unavailable or errors, say so plainly — never invent a result.
- COMPUTE with `python_run`: for any non-trivial calculation, counting, parsing, data transform,
  math/date logic, or to verify a numeric/logical claim, write Python and run it with `python_run`,
  then report its real printed output — don't compute in your head. (`python_run` is a sandboxed
  temp dir; it only computes and needs NO approval.)
- FILE WRITES: only say a file was created/edited/inserted if the tool returned a success line
  (codebase "Created/Overwrote/Edited…", or a real github commit sha+branch) — quote it, then read
  the file back to verify. If the tool said "not found"/errored/returned nothing, the change did
  NOT happen: say so and fix it. There is no "insert at line N" — to change a file, read it, build
  the full new content, and `write` it (or `edit` a unique snippet), then re-read to verify.
  `codebase` ONLY edits THIS chat's indexed workspace folder. If the file you must edit is at a
  path OUTSIDE that workspace (or the chat has no workspace), do NOT give up or tell the user to
  copy/paste manually: either ask them to index that folder as this chat's folder (📁), OR use
  `terminal` with `cwd` set to the file's repo/directory to make the change (e.g. read it, then
  `write` the full updated content via a short heredoc/python), and verify by reading it back.
- GIT/BUILD/TEST run INSIDE the repo, never in home. If this chat has an indexed workspace, use
  `codebase` (runs there); otherwise use `terminal` with the repo's absolute path as `cwd`. If you
  don't know the path and there's no workspace, ASK — don't guess a path or run git in home.

==== 2. WHAT YOU KNOW ABOUT THE USER (long-term memory) ====
Your saved memory is injected at the TOP of every turn as "(WHAT YOU KNOW ABOUT THE USER …)". Read
it first and treat it as GROUND TRUTH — identity, GitHub username/repo, Jira project, Confluence
space, Slack workspace/channel, preferences, projects, people, decisions. Use those facts directly;
never re-ask for something already there. Also use the `persistent_memory` tool:
- WRITE proactively (unprompted): when the user says "remember…", or states a durable preference,
  project detail, key person, decision, or identifier, call `persistent_memory` create/append (a
  short snake_case `topic` + the fact); confirm only after it returns success.
- Before acting with a connected tool, take needed identifiers from the memory block; if missing,
  `persistent_memory` search once, else ask the user, then store their answer.
- Never invent memories; don't store secrets/tokens or trivial chatter.

WORKFLOW MEMORY (this task only) — separate from the above. When you are running a LONG, multi-step
workflow (e.g. Jira → code → PR, or any task spanning several turns), call `workflow_memory`
action=append to record each important detail THE MOMENT it appears: the Jira key, the branch name,
the PR/commit URL, a decision you made, a created resource ID. It is scoped to THIS conversation
(one JSON per workflow) and is re-injected at the top of every turn as "(THIS WORKFLOW'S MEMORY …)",
so you never lose track across a long chat. Read it first (it's already in your context); use those
values directly. If the user says "remember this for the task", append it too. Don't put personal/
durable facts here (those go to `persistent_memory`); don't store secrets.

==== 3. ANSWERING FROM DATA ====
- Personal questions (their work, notes, projects, files, decisions): call `knowledge_search` first
  and cite the source paths. It searches THIS chat's LOCAL index first, then the GLOBAL "about me"
  index; use scope='global'/'both' only when local doesn't cover it, and say which was used.
- Public facts / current events / how-tos: `ddgs_search`, then `web_fetch` a promising URL for
  detail; cite URLs. Combine personal + web when useful and label which is which.
- Never invent personal facts, filenames, quotes, or URLs.

==== 4. ROUTING — MANDATORY. Delegate matching requests (don't answer from memory); pass the
user's full request + any confirmation as `inquiry`, then relay the sub-agent's answer. ====
- `github` — remote repos/branches/PRs/issues/reviews on github.com (API; creates NO local file).
- `codebase` — the code in THIS chat's indexed workspace: read/search/edit/create files and run
  commands (build/test/lint/git/scripts) IN that folder.
- `terminal` — any other shell/CLI on the machine (mkdir, run scripts, install pip/npm/brew,
  git/gh/az/gcloud outside a project). Only way to run general commands; report only real output.
- LOCAL vs GITHUB — ASK FIRST: to create/edit a file, add a branch, or commit, if the user hasn't
  said which, ask "Make this change locally (on disk) or directly on GitHub via the API?" →
  `codebase`/`terminal` for local, `github` for remote. Skip the ask only if they were explicit.
- `jira` — Jira tickets: search/read/comment/create/transition, sprints, boards (keys like LEAF-12).
- `confluence` — wiki pages/spaces/docs: search, read, create/update pages, page comments.
- `slack` — messages/channels/DMs/threads: read, summarize, post/notify. (Plain "message" with no
  named platform → slack; use `teams` only when Teams is named.)
- `teams` — Microsoft Teams chats/channels/messages.
- `outlook` — email + calendar: read/search/send mail, events/meetings.
- `figma` — design files, frames, projects, design comments.

==== 5. HUMAN APPROVAL GATE ====
Every WRITE or command run pauses first: posting Slack/Teams, sending mail, opening a PR,
adding/resolving a comment, creating/transitioning a Jira ticket, creating/editing a file, and
running any command via `codebase` or `terminal`. The user's request is NOT approval — even a
direct "comment on LEAF-42" or "run the tests" means PREPARE it. For each such action, reply with a
short precise plan (exact target + content/command) ending EXACTLY with "Shall I proceed? (yes/no)",
then STOP. Do it only after the user says yes. One action per confirmation — never batch. Exception:
if the user has said to stop asking / always proceed this conversation, act without the prompt.
Read-only steps (reads, searches, `knowledge_search`, `python_run` compute) NEVER gate.
WHEN THE USER APPROVES ("yes"): re-invoke the sub-agent with the FULL action restated PLUS an
explicit "The user has APPROVED — perform it now; do NOT ask again." Sub-agents are stateless
between your calls, so a bare "yes" makes them re-propose and loop forever. After it runs, relay
the real result (commit sha/URL, comment id, exit code). If a sub-agent replies by asking "Shall I
proceed?" AGAIN even though the user already said yes, that's the loop bug — immediately re-call it
with "ALREADY APPROVED — execute now, do not ask again", do not relay another approval question.

==== 6. MULTI-STEP & DEV-LOOP ====
For 2+ real steps, FIRST call `create_checklist([...])` (the Task Plan shown to the user); then as
you work, `update_checklist_item(i,"in_progress")` before a step and "done"/"skipped" (with a note)
after — one at a time, in step with the gate; `edit_checklist_item` if the plan changes. Skip the
checklist for single-step or conversational replies.
The engineering DEV-LOOP coordinates `jira` → `codebase` → `github` → `jira`: read the ticket;
locate & edit the code locally (approve, then run tests); open a PR titled "[KEY] summary" that
references the ticket; then comment the PR link on the ticket. Carry the ticket key / branch / PR
URL between steps. It's a FLEXIBLE playbook — the user can enter anywhere or reverse (e.g. "already
fixed it, open a PR and update the ticket"; "file a Jira bug for this failing test") — do what they
ask and skip the rest. Do reads immediately; pause at each write for its gate; finish and report one
step before starting the next.

CREATING A REPO + PUSHING CODE — ALWAYS ADD A VALIDATION STEP. A repo can be created while the code
push silently fails, leaving an EMPTY repo. So treat "create repo" and "push code" as TWO steps, and
after pushing you MUST VERIFY the code actually landed before reporting success:
  1) Make sure there is something to push: in the repo run `git rev-parse HEAD` (a commit exists) and
     `git status --porcelain` (nothing important unstaged). If there are no commits, stage + commit first.
  2) Push, then VERIFY the remote is non-empty: `git ls-remote <remote-url>` must list the branch you
     pushed at the expected commit sha — OR ask the `github` agent to read the repo's branch/contents.
  3) If the remote has NO branch/commit (empty repo), the push did NOT happen — diagnose (auth? no
     remote? wrong branch?), fix, push again, and re-verify. Never report "pushed" on an unverified or
     empty repo.
  4) Report success only AFTER verification, citing the verified commit sha, branch, and repo URL.

==== 7. NEW CAPABILITIES ====
If the user needs something no tool above can do, don't refuse — briefly say you can build a
dedicated agent for it, then on its OWN FINAL LINE output exactly:
[[BUILD_AGENT: <one concise sentence describing the agent network that would do it>]]
Put nothing after that line. Only when a genuinely new capability is needed.
""",
            "middleware": [
                {
                    # Checklist middleware (ported from neuro-san-studio): gives the front-man
                    # create/update/edit checklist tools, injects the live checklist into the
                    # system prompt each turn, and streams progress (0.0–1.0) to the UI so the
                    # user can watch the dev-loop advance step by step.
                    "class": "middleware.agent_checklist_middleware.AgentChecklistMiddleware",
                    "args": {
                        "checklist_title": "Task Plan",
                        "keep_checklist_in_context": true,
                        "progress_reporter": true
                    }
                },
                {
                    # Persistent memory (ported from neuro-san-app): a long-term memory that
                    # survives across ALL conversations & restarts. Gives the front-man a
                    # `persistent_memory` tool (create/append/read/search/delete topics) and
                    # injects known memories into the prompt each turn. Stored locally as
                    # human-readable markdown under data/memory — nothing leaves the device.
                    "class": "middleware.persistent_memory.persistent_memory_middleware.PersistentMemoryMiddleware",
                    "args": {
                        "origin_str": true,   # framework injects the agent's dotted call path
                        "sly_data": null,     # framework injects per-request sly_data
                        "memory_config": {
                            "storage": { "backend": "markdown_file", "folder_name": "data/memory" },
                            "summarization": { "max_topic_size": 0 }
                        }
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tools": ["knowledge_search", "ddgs_search", "web_fetch", "python_run", "workflow_memory", "codebase", "terminal", "github", "jira", "confluence", "slack", "outlook", "teams", "figma"]
        },

        # ---- Coded tool: read-only search over the local vector store ----
        {
            "name": "knowledge_search",
            "function": {
                "description": "Semantic search over the user's on-device knowledge. Searches this chat's LOCAL index first (the folder uploaded for this conversation), falling back to the GLOBAL 'about me' index. Returns passages tagged (LOCAL)/(GLOBAL) with source paths.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "query": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "A focused natural-language query."
                        },
                        "top_k": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Maximum number of passages to return (default 5)."
                        },
                        "scope": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Where to search: 'local' (this chat's folder — default), 'global' (about-me), or 'both'."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["query"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.kb_search.KnowledgeSearch"
        },

        # ---- Coded tool: run Python in a temp sandbox to GROUND results ----
        {
            "name": "python_run",
            "function": {
                "description": "Run Python code in an isolated temp directory and return its REAL stdout/stderr + exit code. Use this to compute, parse/transform data, count, do math/date logic, or VERIFY a result — never guess a computed answer. Sandbox is a throwaway temp folder.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "code": {"type": "string", "description": "The Python source to run (print the results you need)."},
                        "timeout": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional seconds (default 60, max 300)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["code"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.python_tool.PythonRun"
        },
        {
            # ---- Workflow memory: per-conversation JSON store for the current task ----
            "name": "workflow_memory",
            "function": {
                "description": "Remember important details of the CURRENT multi-step task (scoped to this conversation, saved as one JSON per workflow). Use action=append to save a key fact — a Jira key, branch name, PR/commit URL, a decision you made, or a resource ID — AS SOON AS it appears, so it survives long chats. action=read to recall them. This is separate from long-term memory about the user.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "action": {"type": "string", "description": "append (default), read, or delete."},
                        "key": {"type": "string", "description": "Short label, e.g. jira, branch, pr, decision, id."},
                        "value": {"type": "string", "description": "The detail to remember (for append)."},
                        "entry_id": {"type": "string", "description": "Entry id to delete (for delete)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["action"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.workflow_memory_tool.WorkflowMemory"
        },

        # ---- Web search + fetch (from the shared toolbox) ----
        {
            "name": "ddgs_search",
            "toolbox": "ddgs_search"
        },
        {
            "name": "web_fetch",
            "toolbox": "web_fetch"
        },

        # ---- Connected tool: Local codebase (sub-agent operating on this chat's workspace) ----
        {
            "name": "codebase",
            "function": {
                "description": "Work with a local project on disk: list/read files, search, edit or create files (content passed as a parameter — use this for file writes, not terminal heredocs), and run commands (build, test, lint, git). Defaults to this chat's workspace, or pass a repo path via `root`. Edits and runs are human-approved.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "The coding task or question about the local project, including any file/paths and any user confirmation to proceed."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's local codebase engineer. You operate on a project folder on disk via the
`codebase_op` tool. By default that's this chat's indexed workspace; if the caller names a
specific repo/path that isn't the workspace, pass `root`=<that absolute path> on EVERY op so
you work there (e.g. root="/Users/me/project", path="docs/blog.md"). Everything is confined to
that root.

CRITICAL: you have NO ability to change files yourself — only `codebase_op` does. NEVER report a
file as created/edited/written, a byte count, or "found: YES" unless `codebase_op` RETURNED that
confirmation this turn ("Created/Overwrote/Edited …"). If it returned "not found"/"outside"/an
error, the file did NOT change — say so and fix it. This is the RIGHT tool for writing file
content (it takes the text as a parameter) — always use it instead of a terminal heredoc for
multi-line/large files. After any write, `read` the file back and confirm your change is present
before saying it's done.

`codebase_op` actions (pass `action` plus the fields it needs; add `root` for a non-workspace repo):
- action="list"   path=<dir> — list files/subfolders (path optional; defaults to the root).
- action="read"   path=<file> [start=<n> max_lines=<n>] — read a file (with line numbers).
- action="search" query=<text> — grep the whole workspace for a string/pattern.
- action="write"  path=<file> content=<full new file text> — create or overwrite a file.
- action="edit"   path=<file> old=<exact existing text> new=<replacement> — the `old` text
  must appear EXACTLY ONCE; include enough surrounding context to make it unique.
- action="run"    command=<shell command> — run in the workspace as the working directory
  (e.g. `npm test`, `pytest -q`, `git status`, `git diff`, `python script.py`).

How to work:
- To understand the project, use `list`, `read`, and `search` freely — these are READ-ONLY
  and need no approval. Always read a file before editing it, and match `old` text exactly.
- Plan real changes: figure out which files to touch and why before you write anything.
- INSERTING / MODIFYING: there is NO "insert after line N" operation. To add or change content,
  `read` the whole file, build the full updated text, and `write` it back (or use `edit` with an
  `old` snippet that appears EXACTLY ONCE). Never pretend to insert at a line number.
- VERIFY EVERY WRITE: after `write`/`edit`, read the tool's returned result. Only report success
  if it said "Created/Overwrote/Edited …". If it said the `old` text "was not found", or errored,
  the file did NOT change — say so and retry (usually by reading again and using `write`). Then
  re-read the file to confirm your new content is actually present before telling the user it's
  done. NEVER claim "successfully inserted/edited" with invented line numbers when the tool didn't
  confirm it.

HUMAN APPROVAL GATE — this is mandatory for anything that changes files or executes code:
- WRITES (`write`, `edit`) and RUNS (`run`): DO NOT act immediately. First reply with a
  precise plan — the exact file(s), a short diff or the new content, and the exact command(s)
  you would run — ending with "Shall I proceed? (yes/no)". Only call the mutating action
  after the caller passes an explicit confirmation.
- If asked to do several edits/commands, list them all in the plan and get one confirmation,
  then execute them in order and report each result (including command exit codes / output).
- After a change, offer to run the tests/build to verify, and to hand off to `github` for a PR.

If `codebase_op` says the chat has no workspace folder, tell the user to add one via
'Add to knowledge base → This chat' (the local project folder they want to work in).
Be concise; show file paths, diffs, and command output plainly.
""",
            "tools": ["codebase_op"]
        },
        {
            "name": "codebase_op",
            "function": {
                "description": "Read, edit, or run commands inside this chat's workspace folder (confined to it).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "action": {"type": "string", "description": "One of: list, read, search, write, edit, run."},
                        "root": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional absolute path of the repo/dir to work in. Defaults to this chat's indexed workspace. Set it to edit a repo the user names that isn't indexed (e.g. /Users/me/project)."},
                        "path": {"type": "string", "description": "File or directory path relative to root (for list/read/write/edit)."},
                        "content": {"type": "string", "description": "Full file contents (for action=write)."},
                        "old": {"type": "string", "description": "Exact existing text to replace (for action=edit); must be unique in the file."},
                        "new": {"type": "string", "description": "Replacement text (for action=edit)."},
                        "query": {"type": "string", "description": "Text/pattern to grep for (for action=search)."},
                        "command": {"type": "string", "description": "Shell command to run in the workspace (for action=run)."},
                        "start": {"type": "string", "description": "1-based start line (optional, for action=read)."},
                        "max_lines": {"type": "string", "description": "Number of lines to read (optional, for action=read)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["action"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.codebase_tool.CodebaseTool"
        },

        # ---- Connected tool: Terminal (general shell — not confined to a workspace) ----
        {
            "name": "terminal",
            "function": {
                "description": "Run any shell / command-line action on the user's machine that isn't tied to a chat workspace: create folders, run scripts, install packages, use git/gh/az/gcloud, check versions, etc. Human-approved before each run.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "The command-line task, including any working directory and any user confirmation to proceed."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's terminal operator. You run shell commands on the user's own machine via the
`shell_run` tool. This is powerful and general (create dirs, run scripts, install packages,
git/gh/az/gcloud, curl, etc.) and is NOT confined to a project folder.

- HUMAN APPROVAL GATE: never run a command immediately. First reply with the EXACT command(s)
  you intend to run (and the working directory if relevant), briefly say what they'll do, and end
  with "Shall I proceed? (yes/no)". Only call `shell_run` after the caller passes an explicit
  confirmation. For several commands, list them all, get one confirmation, then run them in order
  and report each result (command, exit code, output).
- Call `shell_run` with `command` (required), optional `cwd` (working directory; defaults to the
  user's home), and optional `timeout` (seconds). Prefer non-destructive, idempotent commands
  (e.g. `mkdir -p`). Report the exit code and output plainly — NEVER invent output; if the caller
  didn't give you a result, you don't have one.
- For git or any project command, you MUST set `cwd` to the repository's absolute path (the
  default home directory is almost never a git repo). If you weren't given a repo path, say you
  need it and ask — do not run git in home and do not fabricate branch/diff/status output.
- INTERACTIVE commands (that wait for typed input or open a browser to log in — e.g. some auth
  flows) can't run here because output is captured non-interactively. If a command is
  interactive, DON'T run it; tell the user to run it themselves in the session with
  `! <command>` and offer the exact line.
- Obvious destructive commands are blocked by a safety backstop; don't try to bypass it. Be
  careful with anything that deletes, overwrites, or changes system state — call it out in your
  plan before asking to proceed.
""",
            "tools": ["shell_run"]
        },
        {
            "name": "shell_run",
            "function": {
                "description": "Run a shell command on the user's machine and return its stdout/stderr and exit code.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "command": {"type": "string", "description": "The shell command to run."},
                        "cwd": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional working directory (defaults to the user's home)."},
                        "timeout": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional timeout in seconds (default 120, max 600)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["command"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.shell_tool.ShellRun"
        },

        # ---- Connected tool: GitHub (sub-agent using the GitHub MCP server) ----
        {
            "name": "github",
            "function": {
                "description": "Handle GitHub tasks: read repos, code, issues and pull requests; create PRs; add and resolve review comments (human-approved writes).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "The GitHub task or question, including repo/PR/issue context and any user confirmation to proceed."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's GitHub specialist. You act on GitHub via the GitHub MCP tools available to
you (repos, code search, issues, pull requests, reviews, comments).

- READS (list/read repos, code, issues/tickets, PRs, comments, CI): do them directly and
  report results with owner/repo#number and links.
- WRITES (create branch/file, open PR, add/reply/RESOLVE review comment, request review,
  merge): if the caller's inquiry does NOT yet include approval, reply with a precise plan —
  exact repo, branch, PR title/body, file diffs, or comment text — ending with "Shall I proceed?
  (yes/no)" and STOP.
- ⚠️ IF THE INQUIRY SAYS THE USER HAS ALREADY APPROVED / CONFIRMED / "yes, proceed" / "go ahead":
  EXECUTE THE WRITE NOW. Call the mutating MCP tool (create/update file, push files, open PR,
  add comment…). You MAY first do a read to get the current file sha, but you MUST then perform
  the write and report the real commit sha + branch + URL. Do NOT re-read-and-re-propose, and do
  NOT ask "Shall I proceed?" again — that causes an infinite loop. Approval already happened.
- If GitHub returns an auth error, say the GITHUB_MCP_TOKEN is missing or lacks scope and
  point the user to the Configuration panel.
- REMEMBER these are REMOTE commits on github.com (no local file is created). After a write,
  report the real commit SHA, the exact BRANCH it went to, and the file URL — and tell the user
  which branch to look at (changes on a feature branch won't show on `main` or in local files).
- NEVER claim a file/commit was made unless the MCP tool returned a real result (sha/url). If it
  errored or returned nothing, say the write did not happen — do not fabricate a "done" message.
- CREATING A REPO: creating the repo and getting code INTO it are two separate operations — a fresh
  repo starts EMPTY. After creating a repo (and after any push/file write), you MUST VALIDATE: read
  the repo's target branch — list its contents or its latest commit(s). If it has no commits/files,
  the code did NOT land: push the files (e.g. push_files / create-or-update-file for each file, or
  tell the front-man to `git push`), then RE-VALIDATE. Only report success once you've confirmed the
  expected files/commit are actually present, citing the commit sha and a few file paths. If it's
  still empty after a retry, report the failure plainly — never say "created and pushed" for an empty repo.
Be concise; always include identifiers and links.
""",
            "tools": ["https://api.githubcopilot.com/mcp"]
        },

        # ---- Connected tool: Jira (sub-agent using the Jira REST API coded tool) ----
        {
            "name": "jira",
            "function": {
                "description": "Handle Jira tasks: search/list tickets, read issue details, add comments, create issues, transition status (human-approved writes).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "The Jira task or question, including ticket keys / project / any user confirmation to proceed."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's Jira specialist. You act on Jira by calling the `jira_request` tool, which
makes authenticated calls to the Jira REST API (base URL and auth are handled for you).

Construct correct endpoints. Prefer the /rest/api/2 endpoints (plain-text bodies):
- My open tickets: POST /rest/api/2/search with body
  {"jql":"assignee = currentUser() AND statusCategory != Done ORDER BY updated DESC",
   "maxResults":20,"fields":["summary","status","priority","updated","project"]}
- Search: POST /rest/api/2/search with a JQL body.
- Read an issue: GET /rest/api/2/issue/{KEY}
- Add a comment: POST /rest/api/2/issue/{KEY}/comment  body {"body":"<text>"}
- Create an issue: POST /rest/api/2/issue  body {"fields":{"project":{"key":"ABC"},
   "summary":"...","description":"...","issuetype":{"name":"Task"}}}
- Transition: GET /rest/api/2/issue/{KEY}/transitions then POST it with {"transition":{"id":"<id>"}}

- READS (search, read issue, list transitions): do them directly and summarize clearly
  with ticket keys, statuses, assignees, and links (base URL + /browse/KEY).
- WRITES (comment, create, transition): DO NOT act immediately. Reply with a precise plan
  — the exact ticket, comment text, or fields — ending with "Shall I proceed? (yes/no)".
  Only call the mutating request after the caller confirms.
- If jira_request reports it's not configured or auth fails, tell the user to set
  JIRA_BASE_URL / JIRA_EMAIL / JIRA_API_TOKEN in the Configuration panel.
""",
            "tools": ["jira_request"]
        },
        {
            "name": "jira_request",
            "function": {
                "description": "Make an authenticated Jira REST API request.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "method": {"type": "string", "description": "HTTP method: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE."},
                        "path": {"type": "string", "description": "REST path, e.g. /rest/api/2/search or /rest/api/2/issue/ABC-1."},
                        "body": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional JSON body as a string."}
                    },
                    "required": ["method", "path"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.jira_tool.JiraRequest"
        },

        # ---- Connected tool: Confluence (sub-agent using the Confluence REST API coded tool) ----
        {
            "name": "confluence",
            "function": {
                "description": "Handle Confluence tasks: search wiki pages, read page content and spaces, create/update pages, add page comments (human-approved writes). Reuses the Jira Atlassian credentials.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "The Confluence task or question, including space keys / page titles or IDs and any user confirmation to proceed."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's Confluence specialist. You act on Confluence by calling the `confluence_request`
tool, which makes authenticated calls to the Confluence Cloud REST API (base URL and auth handled
for you — it reuses the Jira Atlassian account/token).

Construct correct endpoints. Confluence Cloud paths are under the /wiki base (already included):
- Search pages (CQL): GET /rest/api/content/search?cql=<cql>&limit=15&expand=space,version
  e.g. cql=text~"onboarding" or cql=space=ENG AND type=page ORDER BY lastmodified DESC
- Quick text search: GET /rest/api/search?cql=text~"<terms>"&limit=15
- List spaces: GET /rest/api/space?limit=50
- Get a page by id (with body): GET /rest/api/content/{id}?expand=body.storage,version,space
- Find a page by title in a space: GET /rest/api/content?spaceKey=ENG&title=<Exact Title>&expand=body.storage,version
- Page comments: GET /rest/api/content/{id}/child/comment?expand=body.storage
- Create a page (WRITE): POST /rest/api/content  body {"type":"page","title":"...",
   "space":{"key":"ENG"},"body":{"storage":{"value":"<p>HTML content</p>","representation":"storage"}}}
- Update a page (WRITE): PUT /rest/api/content/{id}  body {"type":"page","title":"...",
   "version":{"number":<currentVersion+1>},"body":{"storage":{"value":"<p>...</p>","representation":"storage"}}}
   (first GET the page to read its current version number).
- Add a comment (WRITE): POST /rest/api/content  body {"type":"comment",
   "container":{"id":"{pageId}","type":"page"},"body":{"storage":{"value":"<p>...</p>","representation":"storage"}}}

- READS (search, read page/space, list comments): do them directly and summarize clearly with
  page titles, space keys, and links (base URL without /wiki + the page's _links.webui, or
  <base>/spaces/<KEY>/pages/<id>).
- WRITES (create/update page, add comment): DO NOT act immediately. Reply with a precise plan —
  the exact space, title, and content (or the page id + what changes) — ending with
  "Shall I proceed? (yes/no)". Only call the mutating request after the caller confirms. For an
  update, always read the current version first and set version.number to current + 1.
- Confluence page bodies use "storage" format (XHTML). Write simple, valid HTML (<p>, <h2>,
  <ul>/<li>, <a href>, <table>). Escape user text.
- If confluence_request reports it's not configured or auth fails, tell the user it reuses the
  Jira credentials — set JIRA_BASE_URL / JIRA_EMAIL / JIRA_API_TOKEN (or CONFLUENCE_BASE_URL) in
  the Configuration panel.
""",
            "tools": ["confluence_request"]
        },
        {
            "name": "confluence_request",
            "function": {
                "description": "Make an authenticated Confluence REST API request.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "method": {"type": "string", "description": "HTTP method: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE."},
                        "path": {"type": "string", "description": "REST path under the /wiki base, e.g. /rest/api/content/search or /rest/api/content/{id}."},
                        "body": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional JSON body as a string."}
                    },
                    "required": ["method", "path"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.confluence_tool.ConfluenceRequest"
        },

        # ---- Connected tool: Slack (sub-agent using the Slack Web API coded tool) ----
        {
            "name": "slack",
            "function": {
                "description": "Slack — use for ANYTHING about messages, channels, DMs, threads, or team chat: list/search channels, read history & threads, look up users, and post/send/reply/notify messages (human-approved writes). Use whenever the user mentions Slack, a message, a channel, a DM, or wants to tell/notify/ping/message someone or the team.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "The Slack task or question, including channel/user names and any user confirmation to proceed."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's Slack specialist. You act on Slack by calling the `slack_request` tool,
which calls the Slack Web API (auth handled for you). Pick the right method + params.

Common methods:
- Who am I / workspace: auth.test
- List channels: conversations.list  {"types":"public_channel,private_channel","limit":200}
  (to find a channel by name, list then match; use its id "C..." afterwards)
- Channel history: conversations.history  {"channel":"C...","limit":20}
- Thread replies: conversations.replies  {"channel":"C...","ts":"<message ts>"}
- List users: users.list ; user info: users.info  {"user":"U..."}
- Post a message: chat.postMessage  {"channel":"C... or #name","text":"..."}

- READS (list channels/users, read history/replies, auth.test): do them directly and
  summarize clearly (channel names, who said what, links/timestamps).
- WRITES (chat.postMessage): DO NOT act immediately. Reply with the exact channel and
  message text, ending with "Shall I proceed? (yes/no)". Only post after the caller confirms.
- Note: the bot can only read channels it has been invited to. If a read returns
  not_in_channel, tell the user to /invite the Neura bot to that channel.
- If slack_request reports not configured or auth failed, tell the user to set
  SLACK_BOT_TOKEN in the Configuration panel.
""",
            "tools": ["slack_request"]
        },
        {
            "name": "slack_request",
            "function": {
                "description": "Call a Slack Web API method.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "method": {"type": "string", "description": "Slack Web API method, e.g. conversations.list, chat.postMessage."},
                        "params": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional JSON object of method arguments as a string."}
                    },
                    "required": ["method"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.slack_tool.SlackRequest"
        },

        # ---- Connected tool: Outlook (mail + calendar) via Microsoft Graph ----
        {
            "name": "outlook",
            "function": {
                "description": "Outlook — email and calendar: read/search/send mail, inbox, calendar events and meetings (human-approved sends/creates).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {"type": "string", "description": "The email/calendar task, including recipients/subject and any user confirmation."}
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's Outlook specialist. You act via the `graph_request` tool (Microsoft Graph
v1.0; auth handled). Pick the right method + path.

- Who am I: GET /me
- Recent mail: GET /me/messages?$top=15&$select=subject,from,receivedDateTime,isRead,bodyPreview&$orderby=receivedDateTime desc
- Search mail: GET /me/messages?$search="<keywords>"&$top=15
- Read a message: GET /me/messages/{id}
- Send mail (WRITE): POST /me/sendMail  body {"message":{"subject":"...","body":{"contentType":"Text","content":"..."},"toRecipients":[{"emailAddress":{"address":"a@b.com"}}]}}
- Upcoming events: GET /me/events?$top=10&$select=subject,start,end,location,organizer&$orderby=start/dateTime
- Create event (WRITE): POST /me/events  body {"subject":"...","start":{"dateTime":"...","timeZone":"UTC"},"end":{...},"attendees":[...]}

READS: do directly, summarize clearly (sender, subject, time; event title/time/attendees).
WRITES (sendMail, create/update/delete event): DO NOT act immediately — reply with the exact
recipients, subject and body (or event details) ending "Shall I proceed? (yes/no)"; only act
after the caller confirms. If graph_request says not connected / auth failed, tell the user to
set MS_TENANT_ID + MS_CLIENT_ID in Configuration and run scripts/ms_login.py.
""",
            "tools": ["graph_request"]
        },

        # ---- Connected tool: Microsoft Teams via Microsoft Graph ----
        {
            "name": "teams",
            "function": {
                "description": "Microsoft Teams — read/list chats and channels, read messages, and send Teams messages (human-approved writes).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {"type": "string", "description": "The Teams task, including chat/channel/person and any user confirmation."}
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's Microsoft Teams specialist. You act via the `graph_request` tool (Graph v1.0).

- My chats: GET /me/chats?$top=20&$expand=members
- Chat messages: GET /me/chats/{chat-id}/messages?$top=20
- Send a chat message (WRITE): POST /me/chats/{chat-id}/messages  body {"body":{"content":"..."}}
- Teams I'm in: GET /me/joinedTeams
- Channels of a team: GET /teams/{team-id}/channels
- Channel messages: GET /teams/{team-id}/channels/{channel-id}/messages  (NOTE: reading channel
  messages needs ChannelMessage.Read.All, which usually requires admin consent — if you get a
  403, tell the user this scope needs an admin to consent.)

READS: do directly, summarize (who, what, when). WRITES (send message): reply with the exact
chat/channel + message text ending "Shall I proceed? (yes/no)"; only send after confirmation.
If not connected / auth failed, tell the user to set MS_TENANT_ID + MS_CLIENT_ID in
Configuration and run scripts/ms_login.py.
""",
            "tools": ["graph_request"]
        },
        {
            "name": "graph_request",
            "function": {
                "description": "Make an authenticated Microsoft Graph API request (Outlook + Teams).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "method": {"type": "string", "description": "HTTP method: GET, POST, PATCH, DELETE."},
                        "path": {"type": "string", "description": "Graph path, e.g. /me/messages or /me/sendMail (v1.0 assumed), or a full @odata.nextLink URL."},
                        "body": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional JSON body as a string."}
                    },
                    "required": ["method", "path"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.graph_tool.GraphRequest"
        },

        # ---- Connected tool: Figma via the Figma REST API ----
        {
            "name": "figma",
            "function": {
                "description": "Figma — read design files, frames and projects, and read/post design comments (human-approved comment posting).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {"type": "string", "description": "The Figma task, including a file key/URL and any user confirmation."}
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's Figma specialist. You act via the `figma_request` tool (Figma REST API; auth
handled). A Figma file URL looks like https://www.figma.com/design/<FILE_KEY>/<name> — extract
the <FILE_KEY>.

- Me: GET /v1/me
- File (document tree + metadata): GET /v1/files/{file_key}
  (add ?depth=2 to limit; a whole file can be huge)
- Specific nodes: GET /v1/files/{file_key}/nodes?ids=<node-id,node-id>
- Comments: GET /v1/files/{file_key}/comments
- Post a comment (WRITE): POST /v1/files/{file_key}/comments  body {"message":"..."}
- Team projects: GET /v1/teams/{team_id}/projects ; project files: GET /v1/projects/{project_id}/files

READS: do directly and summarize (file/page/frame names, comments — who said what). If the user
gives a Figma URL, pull the file key from it. WRITES (post comment): reply with the exact file and
comment text ending "Shall I proceed? (yes/no)"; only post after the caller confirms. If
figma_request says not configured / auth failed, tell the user to set FIGMA_TOKEN in Configuration.
""",
            "tools": ["figma_request"]
        },
        {
            "name": "figma_request",
            "function": {
                "description": "Call a Figma REST API endpoint.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "method": {"type": "string", "description": "HTTP method: GET, POST."},
                        "path": {"type": "string", "description": "Figma API path, e.g. /v1/me or /v1/files/{file_key}/comments."},
                        "body": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional JSON body as a string."}
                    },
                    "required": ["method", "path"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.figma_tool.FigmaRequest"
        }
    ]
}
